{
  "text": "The insect wing is one of many kinds of flattened evaginations of the single cell layered insect skin (epithelium). These evaginations flatten (usually dorsoventrally) gradually during the course of the adult development until their two flat surfaces almost completely fuse to each other. See Figure 3 in [CITATION_1] for an example of wing morphogenesis in Drosophila.",
